[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] In computing, a **channel** is a model for interprocess communication and synchronization via message passing.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] A message may be sent over a channel, and another process or thread is able to receive messages sent over a channel it has a reference to, as a stream.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] Different implementations of channels may be buffered or not, and either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] The multithreading library, libthread, which was first created for the operating system Plan 9, offers inter-thread communication based on fixed-size channels.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] The OCaml event module offers typed channels for synchronization.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] When the module's send and receive functions are called, they create corresponding send and receive events which can be synchronized.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] The Love2D library which uses the Lua programming language implements channels with push and pop operations similar to stacks.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] The pop operation will block so as long as there is data resident on the stack.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] The XMOS programming language XC provides a primitive type "Chan" and two operators "<:" and ":>" for sending and receiving data from a channel.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] In this example, two hardware threads are started on the XMOS, running the two lines in the "par" block.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] The first line transmits the number 42 through the channel while the second waits until it is received and sets the value of x.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] The XC language also allows asynchronous receiving on channels through a select statement.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] This snippet of Go code performs similarly to the XC code.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] First the channel c is created, then a goroutine is spawned which sends 42 through the channel.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] When the number is put in the channel x is set to 42.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] Go allows channels to buffer contents, as well as non blocking receiving through the use of a select block.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] Rust provides asynchronous channels for communication between threads.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] Channels allow a unidirectional flow of information between two endpoints: the `Sender` and the `Receiver`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] In addition to their fundamental use for interprocess communication, channels can be used as a primitive to implement various other concurrent programming constructs which can be realized as streams.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] For example, channels can be used to construct futures and promises, where a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/channel-programming] Similarly, iterators can be constructed directly from channels.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] In computer science, **communicating sequential processes** (**CSP**) is a formal language for describing patterns of interaction in concurrent systems.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] It is a member of the family of mathematical theories of concurrency known as process algebras, or process calculi, based on message passing via channels.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] CSP was highly influential in the design of the occam programming language and also influenced the design of programming languages such as Limbo, RaftLib, Erlang, Go, Crystal, and Clojure's core.async.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] CSP was first described by Tony Hoare in a 1978 article, and has since evolved substantially.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] CSP has been practically applied in industry as a tool for specifying and verifying the concurrent aspects of a variety of different systems, such as the T9000 Transputer, as well as a secure e-commerce system.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The theory of CSP itself is also still the subject of active research, including work to increase its range of practical applicability (e.g., increasing the scale of the systems that can be tractably analyzed).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The version of CSP presented in Hoare's original 1978 article was essentially a concurrent programming language rather than a process calculus.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] It had a substantially different syntax than later versions of CSP, did not possess mathematically defined semantics, and was unable to represent unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Programs in the original CSP were written as a parallel composition of a fixed number of sequential processes communicating with each other strictly through synchronous message-passing.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] In contrast to later versions of CSP, each process was assigned an explicit name, and the source or destination of a message was defined by specifying the name of the intended sending or receiving process.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] repeatedly receives a character from the process named `west` and sends that character to process named `east`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] assigns the names `west` to the `DISASSEMBLE` process, `X` to the `COPY` process, and `east` to the `ASSEMBLE` process, and executes these three processes concurrently.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Following the publication of the original version of CSP, Hoare, Stephen Brookes, and A.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Roscoe developed and refined the *theory* of CSP into its modern, process algebraic form.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The approach taken in developing CSP into a process algebra was influenced by Robin Milner's work on the Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and conversely.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The theoretical version of CSP was initially presented in a 1984 article by Brookes, Hoare, and Roscoe, and later in Hoare's book *Communicating Sequential Processes*, which was published in 1985.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] In September 2006, that book was still the third-most cited computer science reference of all time according to Citeseer (albeit an unreliable source due to the nature of its sampling).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The theory of CSP has undergone a few minor changes since the publication of Hoare's book.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Most of these changes were motivated by the advent of automated tools for CSP process analysis and verification.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Roscoe's *The Theory and Practice of Concurrency* describes this newer version of CSP.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] An early and important application of CSP was its use for specification and verification of elements of the INMOS T9000 Transputer, a complex superscalar pipelined processor designed to support large-scale multiprocessing.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] CSP was employed in verifying the correctness of both the processor pipeline and the Virtual Channel Processor, which managed off-chip communications for the processor.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Industrial application of CSP to software design has usually focused on dependable and safety-critical systems.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The modeling and analysis process was able to uncover a number of errors that would have been difficult to detect using testing alone.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Similarly, Praxis High Integrity Systems applied CSP modeling and analysis during the development of software (approximately 100,000 lines of code) for a secure smart-card certification authority to verify that their design was secure and free of deadlock.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Praxis claims that the system has a much lower defect rate than comparable systems.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Since CSP is well-suited to modeling and analyzing systems that incorporate complex message exchanges, it has also been applied to the verification of communications and security protocols.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A prominent example of this sort of application is Lowe's use of CSP and the FDR refinement-checker to discover a previously unknown attack on the Needham–Schroeder public-key authentication protocol, and then to develop a corrected protocol able to defeat the attack.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] As its name suggests, CSP allows the description of systems in terms of component processes that operate independently, and interact with each other solely through message-passing communication.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] However, the *"Sequential"* part of the CSP name is now something of a misnomer, since modern CSP allows component processes to be defined both as sequential processes and as the parallel composition of more primitive processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The relationships between different processes, and the way each process communicates with its environment, are described using various process algebraic operators.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Using this algebraic approach, quite complex process descriptions can be easily constructed from a few primitive elements.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] CSP provides two classes of primitives in its process algebra: events and primitive processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Events represent communications or interactions.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] They are assumed to be instantaneous, and their communication is all that an external ‘environment’ can know about processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] An event is communicated only if the environment allows it.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] If a process does offer an event and the environment allows it, then that event *must* be communicated.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Events may be atomic names (e.g., on, off), compound names (e.g. valve.open, valve.close), or input/output events (e.g., mouse?xy, screen!bitmap).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The set of all events is denoted $\Sigma$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Primitive processes represent fundamental behaviors: examples include $\mathrm {STOP}$ (the process that immediately deadlocks), and $\mathrm {SKIP}$ (the process that immediately terminates successfully).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] CSP has a wide range of algebraic operators.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The principal ones are informally given as follows.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The prefix operator combines an event and a process to produce a new process.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] For example, $a\to P$ is the process that is willing to communicate event a with its environment and, after a , behaves like the process P .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Processes can be defined using recursion.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Where $F(P)$ is any CSP term involving P , the process $\mu P.F(P)$ defines a recursive process given by the equation $P=F(P)$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Recursions can also be defined mutually, such as ${\begin{aligned}&P_{u}=up\to P_{d}\\&P_{d}=down\to P_{u}\\\end{aligned}}$ which defines a pair of mutually recursive processes that alternate between communicating $up$ and $down$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The deterministic (or external) choice operator allows the future evolution of a process to be defined as a choice between two component processes and allows the environment to resolve the choice by communicating an initial event for one of the processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] For example, $(a\to P)\ \Box \ (b\to Q)$ is the process that is willing to communicate the initial events a and b and subsequently behaves as either P or Q , depending on which initial event the environment chooses to communicate.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The nondeterministic (or internal) choice operator allows the future evolution of a process to be defined as a choice between two component processes, but does not allow the environment any control over which one of the component processes will be selected.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] For example, $(a\to P)\sqcap (b\to Q)$ can behave like either $a\to P$ or $b\to Q$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] It can refuse to accept a or b and is only obliged to communicate if the environment offers both a and b .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Nondeterminism can be inadvertently introduced into an ostensibly deterministic choice if the initial events of both sides of the choice are identical.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] So, for example, $(a\to a\to \mathrm {STOP} )\ \Box \ (a\to b\to \mathrm {STOP} )$ and $a\to {\big (}(a\to \mathrm {STOP} )\sqcap (b\to \mathrm {STOP} ){\big )}$ are equivalent.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The interleaving operator represents completely independent concurrent activity.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The process $P\;|||\;Q$ behaves as both P and Q simultaneously.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The events from both processes are arbitrarily interleaved in time.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Interleaving can introduce nondeterminism even if P and Q are both deterministic: if P and Q can both communicate the same event, then $P\;|||\;Q$ nondeterministically chooses which of the two processes communicated that event.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The interface parallel (or generalized parallel) operator represents concurrent activity that requires synchronization between the component processes: for $P\;|[X]|\;Q$ , any event in the interface set $X\subseteq \Sigma$ can only occur when both P and Q are able to engage in that event.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] For example, the process $P\;|[\{a\}]|\;Q$ requires that P and Q must both be able to perform event a before that event can occur.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The hiding operator provides a way to abstract processes by making some events unobservable by the environment. $P\setminus X$ is the process P with the event set X hidden.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A trivial example of hiding is $(a\to P)\setminus \{a\}$ which, assuming that the event a doesn't appear in P , simply reduces to P .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Hidden events are internalized as *τ actions*, which are invisible to and uncontrollable by the environment.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The existence of hiding introduces an additional behaviour called divergence, where an infinite sequence of τ actions is performed.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] This is captured by the process $\mathbf {div}$ , whose behaviour is solely to perform τ actions forever.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] For example, $(\mu P.a\to P)\setminus \{a\}$ is equivalent to $\mathbf {div}$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] One of the archetypal CSP examples is an abstract representation of a chocolate vending machine and its interactions with a person wishing to buy some chocolate.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] This vending machine might be able to carry out two different events, “coin” and “choc”, which represent the insertion of payment and the delivery of a chocolate, respectively.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] These two processes can be put in parallel, so that they can interact with each other.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The behaviour of the composite process depends on the events that the two component processes must synchronise on.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] This is a process that either offers a “choc” event and then stops, or just stops.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] In other words, if we treat the abstraction as an external view of the system (e.g., someone who does not see the decision reached by the person), nondeterminism has been introduced.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The syntax of CSP defines the “legal” ways in which processes and events may be combined.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Let e be an event, b be a boolean, and X be a set of events.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Note that, in the interests of brevity, the syntax presented above omits the $\mathbf {div}$ process, which represents divergence, as well as various operators such as alphabetized parallel, piping, and indexed choices.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] CSP has been imbued with several different formal semantics, which define the *meaning* of syntactically correct CSP expressions.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The theory of CSP includes mutually consistent denotational semantics, algebraic semantics, and operational semantics.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The three major denotational models of CSP are the *traces* model, the *stable failures* model, and the *failures/divergences* model.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Semantic mappings from process expressions to each of these three models provide the denotational semantics for CSP.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Denotational semantics allows several definitions of a partial order of *refinement* on processes, which in turn can be used to elegantly represent several properties on processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Generally, $P\sqsubseteq Q$ denotes Q *refines* P .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The *traces model* defines the meaning of a process expression as the set of sequences of events (traces) that the process can be observed to perform.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] More formally, the traces model ${\mathcal {T}}$ is defined as the set of non-empty prefix-closed subsets of $\Sigma ^{\ast }$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] where $\Sigma ^{\ast }$ is the set of all possible finite sequences of events.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A process P is said to *trace-refine* another Q if and only if $\mathrm {traces} (P)\supseteq \mathrm {traces} (Q)$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] P *trace-refines* Q is denoted $Q\sqsubseteq _{\mathrm {T} }P$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The *stable failures model* ${\mathcal {F}}$ extends the traces model with refusal sets, which are sets of events $X\subseteq \Sigma$ that a process can refuse to perform.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A *failure* is a pair $\left(s,X\right)$ , consisting of a trace s, and a refusal set X which identifies the events that a process may refuse once it has executed the trace s.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The observed behavior of a process in the stable failures model is described by the pair $\left(\mathrm {traces} \left(P\right),\mathrm {failures} \left(P\right)\right)$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A process P *stable-failures-refines* Q if and only if $\mathrm {traces} (P)\supseteq \mathrm {traces} (Q)\land \mathrm {failures} (P)\supseteq \mathrm {failures} (Q)$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] P *stable-failures-refines* Q is denoted $Q\sqsubseteq _{\mathrm {F} }P$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The *failures/divergence model* ${\mathcal {N}}$ further extends the failures model to handle divergence.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A process P *failures-divergences-refines* Q if and only if $\mathrm {failures} _{\bot }(P)\supseteq \mathrm {failures} _{\bot }(Q)\land \mathrm {divergences} (P)\supseteq \mathrm {divergences} (Q)$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] P *failures-divergences refines* Q is denoted $Q\sqsubseteq _{\mathrm {FD} }P$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] One of the most important principles in CSP is the *unique fixed points* (UFP) rule.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Generally, it states that a process which satisfies certain nice properties has a single semantic interpretation.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] It can be used to conclude algebraic proofs that two processes are equal in a model of CSP.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A version for single recursions in the traces model is outlined here.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The operator $\downarrow$ is defined for all processes P , all $n\in \mathbb {N}$ so that $P\downarrow n=\{s\in P:\#s\leq n\}$ , where $\#s$ denotes the length of string s : the set of traces in P of length at most n .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] This allows a metric to be defined on ${\mathcal {T}}$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Informally, a process which agrees on traces with another up to some length is ‘more distant’ from it than one which agrees with it up to a greater length.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] It can be shown that this forms a complete metric space.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A function on trace sets $F:{\mathcal {T}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {T}}$ is called *constructive* if and only if for all processes P , Q , all $n\in \mathbb {N}$ , if $P\downarrow n=Q\downarrow n$ then $F(P)\downarrow (n+1)=F(Q)\downarrow (n+1)$ .
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] This means that a function is constructive if and only if it is a contraction mapping with respect to the metric on trace sets.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] By the Banach fixed-point theorem, if F is a constructive function, it has a unique fixed point.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] This means that if X and Y are processes defined recursively as $X=F(X)$ and $Y=F(Y)$ , then they are equivalent in the traces model.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] UFP can also be extended to mutual recursions (by using vectors of processes) and other models of CSP (e.g., in ${\mathcal {F}}$ by defining the metric as in ${\mathcal {T}}$ , with respect to the trace parts of a process's trace-failure pair).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] It can be derived using UFP (and Tarski's fixed-point theorem), that for monotonic F , a recursive term defined as $X=F(X)$ has the semantic interpretation $\sqcap _{n=0}^{\infty }F^{n}(\bot )$ , where $\bot$ is the least element of the model.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] In the traces, stable failures and failures/divergences models, $\bot =\mathbf {div}$ (equivalent to $\mathrm {STOP}$ in the traces model).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Over the years, a number of tools for analyzing and understanding systems described using CSP have been produced.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Early tool implementations used a variety of machine-readable syntaxes for CSP, making input files written for different tools incompatible.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] However, most CSP tools have now standardized on the machine-readable dialect of CSP devised by Bryan Scattergood, sometimes referred to as CSP*M*.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The CSP*M* dialect of CSP possesses a formally defined operational semantics, which includes an embedded functional programming language.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The most well-known CSP tool is probably *Failures–Divergences Refinement*, which is a commercial product originally developed by Formal Systems (Europe) Ltd.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] FDR applies various state-space compression algorithms to the process LTSs in order to reduce the size of the state-space that must be explored during a refinement check.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] FDR was succeeded by FDR2, FDR3 and FDR4.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The *Adelaide Refinement Checker* (*ARC*) is a CSP refinement checker developed by the Formal Modelling and Verification Group at The University of Adelaide.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] ARC differs from FDR2 in that it internally represents CSP processes as ordered binary decision diagrams (OBDDs), which alleviates the state explosion problem of explicit LTS representations without requiring the use of state-space compression algorithms such as those used in FDR2.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The *ProB* project, which is hosted by the Institut für Informatik, Heinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorf, was originally created to support analysis of specifications constructed in the B method.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] However, it also includes support for analysis of CSP processes both through refinement checking, and LTL model-checking.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] ProB can also be used to verify properties of combined CSP and B specifications.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] A ProBE CSP Animator is integrated in FDR3.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The *Process Analysis Toolkit* (PAT) is a CSP analysis tool developed in the School of Computing at the National University of Singapore.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] PAT is able to perform refinement checking, LTL model-checking, and simulation of CSP and Timed CSP processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The PAT process language extends CSP with support for mutable shared variables, asynchronous message passing, and a variety of fairness and quantitative time-related process constructs such as `deadline` and `waituntil`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The underlying design principle of the PAT process language is to combine a high-level specification language with procedural programs (e.g. an event in PAT may be a sequential program or even an external C# library call) for greater expressiveness.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Mutable shared variables and asynchronous channels provide a convenient syntactic sugar for well-known process modelling patterns used in standard CSP.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The PAT syntax is similar, but not identical, to CSP*M*.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] The principal differences between the PAT syntax and standard CSP*M* are the use of semicolons to terminate process expressions, the inclusion of syntactic sugar for variables and assignments, and the use of slightly different syntax for internal choice and parallel composition.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Inasmuch as it is concerned with concurrent processes that exchange messages, the actor model is broadly similar to CSP.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] Note that the aforementioned properties do not necessarily refer to the original CSP paper by Hoare, but rather the modern incarnation of the idea as seen in implementations such as Go and Clojure's *core.async*.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] In the original paper, channels were not a central part of the specification, and the sender and receiver processes actually identify each other by name.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/communicating-sequential-processes] In 1990, “A Queen’s Award for Technological Achievement [was] conferred ... on [Oxford University] Computing Laboratory.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] In concurrent computing, **deadlock** is any situation in which no member of some group of entities can proceed because each waits for another member, including itself, to take action, such as sending a message or, more commonly, releasing a lock.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlocks are a common problem in multiprocessing systems, parallel computing, and distributed systems, because in these contexts systems often use software or hardware locks to arbitrate shared resources and implement process synchronization.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] In an operating system, a deadlock occurs when a process or thread enters a waiting state because a requested system resource is held by another waiting process, which in turn is waiting for another resource held by another waiting process.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] If a process remains indefinitely unable to change its state because resources requested by it are being used by another process that itself is waiting, then the system is said to be in a deadlock.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] In a communications system, deadlocks occur mainly due to loss or corruption of signals rather than contention for resources.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] *Hold and wait* or *resource holding:* a process is currently holding at least one resource and requesting additional resources which are being held by other processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] *No preemption:* a resource can be released only voluntarily by the process holding it.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] *Circular wait:* each process must be waiting for a resource which is being held by another process, which in turn is waiting for the first process to release the resource.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] In general, there is a set of waiting processes, *P* = {*P*1, *P*2, ..., *P**N*}, such that *P*1 is waiting for a resource held by *P*2, *P*2 is waiting for a resource held by *P*3 and so on until *P**N* is waiting for a resource held by *P*1.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] These four conditions are known as the *Coffman conditions* from their first description in a 1971 article by Edward G.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] While these conditions are sufficient to produce a deadlock on single-instance resource systems, they only indicate the possibility of deadlock on systems having multiple instances of resources.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Most current operating systems cannot prevent deadlocks.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] When a deadlock occurs, different operating systems respond to them in different non-standard manners.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Most approaches work by preventing one of the four *Coffman conditions* from occurring, especially the fourth one.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] In this approach, it is assumed that a deadlock will never occur.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] This is also an application of the Ostrich algorithm.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] This approach was initially used by MINIX and UNIX.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] This is used when the time intervals between occurrences of deadlocks are large and the data loss incurred each time is tolerable.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Ignoring deadlocks can be safely done if deadlocks are formally proven to never occur.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Under the deadlock detection, deadlocks are allowed to occur.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Then the state of the system is examined to detect that a deadlock has occurred and subsequently it is corrected.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] An algorithm is employed that tracks resource allocation and process states, it rolls back and restarts one or more of the processes in order to remove the detected deadlock.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Detecting a deadlock that has already occurred is easily possible since the resources that each process has locked and/or currently requested are known to the resource scheduler of the operating system.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] *Resource preemption:* resources allocated to various processes may be successively preempted and allocated to other processes until the deadlock is broken.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock prevention works by preventing one of the four Coffman conditions from occurring.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Similar to deadlock prevention, deadlock avoidance approach ensures that deadlock will not occur in a system.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] The term "deadlock avoidance" appears to be very close to "deadlock prevention" in a linguistic context, but they are very much different in the context of deadlock handling.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance does not impose any conditions as seen in prevention but, here each resource request is carefully analyzed to see whether it could be safely fulfilled without causing deadlock.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance requires that the operating system be given in advance additional information concerning which resources a process will request and use during its lifetime.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance algorithm analyzes each and every request by examining that there is no possibility of deadlock occurrence in the future if the requested resource is allocated.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] The drawback of this approach is its requirement of information in advance about how resources are to be requested in the future.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] One of the most used deadlock avoidance algorithms is Banker's algorithm.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] A *livelock* is similar to a deadlock, except that the states of the processes involved in the livelock constantly change with regard to one another, none progressing.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Ashcroft in a 1975 paper in connection with an examination of airline booking systems.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Livelock is a special case of resource starvation; the general definition only states that a specific process is not progressing.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Livelock is a risk with some algorithms that detect and recover from *deadlock*.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] If more than one process takes action, the deadlock detection algorithm can be repeatedly triggered.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] This can be avoided by ensuring that only one process (chosen arbitrarily or by priority) takes action.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Unlike in centralized systems, detecting and resolving distributed deadlocks is more complex due to the lack of shared memory and the need for coordination among nodes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] Techniques like wait-for graphs, distributed algorithms (like edge chasing; e.g., Chandy-Misra-Haas), and deadlock prevention (e.g., timeout-based methods) are used to handle such scenarios.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/deadlock-computer-science] The challenge lies in ensuring consistency and avoiding false positives/negatives due to network delays or partial failures.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
