[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] Occam is an imperative procedural language (such as Pascal).
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] It was developed by David May and others at Inmos (trademark INMOS), advised by Tony Hoare, as the native programming language for their transputer microprocessors, but implementations for other platforms are available.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] The most widely known version is occam 2; its programming manual was written by Steven Ericsson-Zenith and others at Inmos.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] In the following examples indentation and formatting are critical for parsing the code: expressions are terminated by the end of the line, lists of expressions need to be on the same level of indentation.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] This feature, named the off-side rule, is also found in other languages such as Haskell and Python.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] Communication between processes work through named *channels*.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] One process outputs data to a channel via `!` while another one inputs data with `?`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] Input and output cannot proceed until the other end is ready to accept or offer data.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] (In the *not proceeding* case it is often said that the process *blocks* on the channel.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] `SEQ` (sequential) introduces a list of expressions that are evaluated sequentially.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] This is not implicit as it is in most other programming languages.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] `PAR` (parallel) begins a list of expressions that may be evaluated concurrently.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] `ALT` (alternative) specifies a list of *guarded* commands.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] The guards are a combination of a Boolean condition and an input expression, both optional.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] Each guard for which the condition is true and the input channel is ready is successful.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] One of the successful alternatives is selected for execution.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] This will read data from channels c1 or c2 (whichever is ready) and pass it into a merged channel.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] If countN reaches 100, reads from the corresponding channel will be disabled.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] A request on the status channel is answered by outputting the counts to `out`.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/occam-programming-language] For a full list of the changes see Appendix P of the Inmos occam 2.1 Reference Manual.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] Hoare developed the sorting algorithm quicksort in 1959–1960.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] He developed Hoare logic, an axiomatic basis for verifying program correctness.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] In the semantics of concurrency, he introduced the formal language communicating sequential processes (CSP) to specify the interactions of concurrent processes, and along with Edsger Dijkstra, formulated the dining philosophers problem.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] From 1977 on, he held positions at the University of Oxford as well as at Microsoft Research in Cambridge.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] Tony Hoare was born in Colombo, Ceylon (now Sri Lanka) on 11 January 1934, to British parents; his father was a colonial civil servant and his mother was the daughter of a tea planter.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] Hoare was privately educated in England at the Dragon School in Oxford and the King's School in Canterbury.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] He then studied Classics and Philosophy ("Greats") at the University of Oxford as an undergraduate student at Merton College, Oxford.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] On graduating in 1956 he did 18 months National Service in the Royal Navy, where he learned Russian.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] He returned to the University of Oxford in 1958 to study for a postgraduate certificate in statistics, and it was here that he began computer programming, having been taught Autocode on the Ferranti Mercury by Leslie Fox.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] He then went to Moscow State University as a British Council exchange student, where he studied machine translation supervised by Andrey Kolmogorov.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] In 1960, Hoare left the Soviet Union and began working at Elliott Brothers Ltd, a small computer manufacturing firm located in London.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] There, he implemented a compiler for the language ALGOL 60 and began developing major algorithms.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] He became the first Christopher Strachey Professor of Computing on its establishment in 1988 until his retirement at Oxford in 2000.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] He was an Emeritus Professor there, and also a principal researcher at Microsoft Research in Cambridge, England.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] For many years under his leadership, Hoare's Oxford department worked on formal specification languages such as CSP and the Z notation.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] A commemorative article of reminiscences was written in tribute to Hoare for his 90th birthday.
[src:communicating-sequential-processes/tony-hoare] In 1962, Hoare married Jill Pym, a member of his research team, with whom he had three children.
